Observing here the gradient property of the effective localization fields  (), one easily recognizes the present source relations () as nothing else than the former charge conservation laws () when the result () for the currents  is observed together with the density derivatives ().
Exchange Dynamics As the preceding single-particle dynamics demonstrates, there is a coupling of the single-particle fields to the exchange fields, see the amplitude equations () and curl relations () for the effective kinetic fields. This coupling shows that the single-particle dynamics decouples from the exchange fields only for the pure states () but not for the mixtures (). Thus, when dealing with the pure states, one can first solve the autonomous single-particle system and substitute this as a kind of rigid background into the exchange dynamics. However for the mixtures, one must solve the single-particle system in one step together with the exchange system because also the latter system couples back to the first system. This coupling is explicitly seen by writing down the source relations for the exchange fields (deducible again from the conservation equation ()):
 
 
 
Observe here that even for the pure states () the exchange fields do not decouple from the single-particle fields. Such a decoupling effect occurs exclusively for the curl relations (to be deduced from the integrability condition()):
 
 
 
Here, the first equation (a) says that  must always be a gradient field which however is clear from its very definition (). Furthermore the vector field  becomes also a gradient field for the pure states (), cf. (c).

Thus the new parametrization yields not only a formal simplification of the whole RST dynamics but makes also the theory more transparent by providing us with a clear subdivision of the field variables into single-particle and exchange objects. As a consequence, one becomes able to discuss the RST predictions in terms of single-particle concepts and exchange interactions.

Bundle Geometry 

Whenever a superselection rule is seen to be in action, such as the present dynamical separation of positive and negative mixtures, one tends to guess that such a strict rule might have to do something with the global topological features of the corresponding field configurations. Indeed it is easily seen from fig.1 that the one-parted hyperboloid , being infinitely connected, cannot be continuously deformed into the two-parted hyperboloid  whose individual parts are simply connected. Therefore it is self-suggesting to guess that this topological arrangement is somehow encoded into the field variables of positive and negative mixtures.  Thus there arises an attractive mathematical problem, namely to identify the place where the two different topologies are buried in the space-time dependence of the field variables.
 
 The answer to this question is the following: Take the renormalization factor  (c) and the mixture variable  () together with the 1-forms  and , cf. (), and construct the 2-form 
 
i.e. in components
 
Then use the field equations for the mixture variable  () and renormalization factor  (c) together with the curl relations for  and  () in order to show that the 2-form  is closed: , i.e. in components
 
Actually  is an element of the deRham cohomology group  over space-time (), and its value upon some 2-cycle  is a fixed integer 
 
being independent of continuous deformations of the closed 2-surface . Furthermore, for the present 2-particle case () the "winding numbers"  are found to be always zero for both types of mixtures, no matter which element  of the corresponding homology group of the underlying space-time is taken as the integral surface. Thus  turns out to be an exact 2-form: , in components
 
with  some appropriate (non-unique) 1-form.

Though both mixtures have the same (trivial) winding numbers , the 2-form  carries nevertheless different topological information. It can namely be shown that  is the Euler class  of appropriate fibre bundles (density bundles , to be constructed below). This means concretely that there exists a regular "density map" () from space-time to the hyperboloids  in 3-dimensional, pseudo-Euclidian density configuration space (fig.1)
 
 
such that the 2-form  () yields just the 2-volume form on those hyperboloids (up to an exact 2-form ):
 
Therefore the winding numbers () measure the surface content (on the hyperboloids ) of the image of the 2-cycle  with respect to the density map  (). But since both hyperboloids  as non-compact 2-surfaces have trivial second homotopy group (), the image of the compact  (e.g. 2-sphere ) under  yields a multiple covering (with alternative orientations) of some subspace of  and this must necessarily imply the vanishing of the winding numbers  (). Would the density map  lead into some image space with non-trivial second homotopy group  (, as it may be expected for particle number ), the winding numbers of positive and negative mixtures could well be different in a non-trivial way.

In what follows a proof is presented for all these claims, leading directly to the central result ().

Density Bundle 
For a deeper understanding of the mixture topology it is highly instructive to evoke the mathematical tool of fibre bundles. Within this framework, one recovers not only the decisive curl relation () (which one could find also by merely applying the dynamical equations in a straight-forward manner) but one becomes capable to identify that relation as the Bianchi identity  for the bundle curvature . In this way one arrives at the true origin of the winding numbers  ().

For the construction of the fibre bundle in question, recall first that the intensity matrix , as an Hermitian -matrix, properly speaking has four independent components. These however could be reduced to only three real components by resorting to a co-moving reference system (the RTB basis ), so that the intensity matrix  reappears as a 3-component object, cf. (). As the three remaining components one may take the overlap density  (), the total density  () and the relative density  () which obey the density dynamcis () and give rise to the introduction of the renormalization factors , ,  (). The interesting point here is now that the latter three objects may be collected into a 3-vector  () as an element of a 3-dimensional real vector fibre over any event  of space-time: 
 
 
 
This 3-dimensional vector fibre is equipped with a Minkowskian fibre metric  so that the normalization constraint (b) simply says that  () is a unit vector
 
namely either "time-like" () or "space-like" (), resp. "light-like" (). 

The next interesting point comes into play when one wishes to equip this density bundle () with a connection (, say). In order to preserve the normalization (), the connection 1-form  must take its values in the 3-dimensional Lorentz algebra . The latter algebra may be thought to be spanned by three anti-Hermitian generators  where the concept of Hermiticity refers here to the Minkowskian metric . This means that when  are the elements of the matrix  and  are the elements of  then we have 
 
