It is thus true that both kinds of mixtures share the triviality of their Euler class , yet there are nevertheless some geometric differences being worth to be considered in some more detail now.

























Discussion 

It is just the emergence of trivial principal bundles in connection with the 2-particle configurations which admits a concrete geometric picture of these
configurations. This appears in form of a local fibre distribution in the
tangent bundle. 

Let us consider the negative mixtures first, for which a   global  section  () exists for the embedding Lorentz
bundle. However since the latter bundle has the same fibre space  as
the principal bundle associated with the tangent bundle of the underlying
space-time, one may look upon  also as a global section of the
(tangent) principal bundle, provided the existence of such global
sections is admitted by the topology of space-time. In order that this condition be satisfied, space-time must namely be a 
  parallelisable  manifold (such as, e.g. the closed Robertson-Walker universe 
 which is topologically the direct product of the 3-sphere 
and real line ). By virtue of their very definition, parallelisable
manifolds admit the existence of a global  frame, i.e. for
the present case of four-dimensional space-time a tetrad of linearly
independent vector fields . These can
be chosen to be orthonormal with respect to the presumed space-time metric

 

The tetrad  may further be taken to be a solution of the transport equations
 
with the connection coefficients  being due to the trivial connection  (), which in general will be a non-metric connection. The vanishing of the curvature  () of  then guarantees that any global tetrad solution  of () is unique over the whole space-time and thus it establishes a global isomorphism of all the tangent fibres. The restriction of the trivial Lorentz connection  to the non-trivial  connection  () geometrically means to omit one of the (space-like) tetrad vectors and to consider the remaining triad 
 
This triad defines a local (1+3) splitting of the tangent fibres. Since
however the curvature  () of  is
proportional to the  generator , it
annihilates the same vectors as does the projector  (), which is nothing else than the square of the generator . But this two-dimensional projector  itself
annihilates a 2-dimensional subspace of any tangent fibre and thus induces a local (2+2)-splitting. In the corresponding 2-distribution, as a sub-distribution of the former () splitting (), the projector  acts as the identity and if this 2-distribution is
integrable, there arises a foliation of space-time into a system of 2-surfaces. The Euler class  () appears then as the intrinsic curvature
of these 2-surfaces. In this sense, the negative two-particle mixtures are
geometrically represented by a system of 2-surfaces which are equipped with a Lorentzian tangent metric. The existence of such a metric is guaranteed by the vanishing of the Euler number  (); and its invariance group consists of the  tranformations being specified by equation ().

On the other hand, the positive mixtures are geometrically characterized by a trivial  connection  () and thus start
with a global triad of tangent vectors  from the very
beginning
 
However such a triad can always be complemented to a tetrad (by selection of
some linearly independent fourth vector) and then the same arguments do apply
as for the negative mixtures. The geometric difference between both mixtures
is that the representative 2-surfaces for the positive mixtures are space-like 
(such that the gauge element  () acts as an ordinary rotation of the
space-like tangent plane of the 2-surfaces) whereas the negative mixtures have 
a (1+1)-dimensional Minkowski plane as their tangent space. 


