The relativistic von Neumann equation () subdivides the density configuration
space into three subsets: the pure states  occupy the Fierz
  cone  , positive mixtures   are geometrically
represented by the two-parted hyperboloid and the negative mixtures 
 by the one-parted hyperboloid. The mixtures approach the
pure states for . The general RST dynamics forbids a
change of the mixture type, cf. (). The positive (negative)
mixtures may be considered as the RST counterparts of the symmetric 
(anti-symmetric) states of the conventional quantum theory.
 
    





